'''Fuzzball routers''' were the first modern [[router (computing)|router]]s on the [[Internet]].<ref>{{cite book|author=Carl Malamud|title=Exploring the Internet: a technical travelogue|publisher=Prentice Hall|isbn=0-13-296898-3|year=1992|pages=88|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YDnbAAAAMAAJ&pg=PA88}}</ref> They were [[Digital Equipment Corporation|DEC]] [[LSI-11]] computers loaded with the Fuzzball software written by [[David L. Mills]] (of the [[University of Delaware]]).<ref>[http://nsf.gov/about/history/nsf0050/internet/fuzzball.htm Fuzzball: The Innovative Router] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20110520060410/http://nsf.gov/about/history/nsf0050/internet/fuzzball.htm |date=2011-05-20 }}</ref><ref name="thefuzz">[http://www.eecis.udel.edu/~mills/database/papers/fuzz.pdf] Mills, D.L. The Fuzzball. Proc. ACM SIGCOMM 88 Symposium (Palo Alto CA, August 1988), 115-122.</ref> The name "Fuzzball" was the [[colloquialism]] for Mills' routing software. Six Fuzzball routers provided the routing backbone of the first 56 kbit/s [[NSFnet]],<ref>[http://www.eecis.udel.edu/~mills/database/papers/bone.pdf] Mills, D.L., and H.-W. Braun. The NSFNET Backbone Network. Proc. ACM SIGCOMM 87 Symposium (Stoweflake VT, August 1987), 191-196</ref><ref>Presentation at the NSFNET Legacy event, 2007. [http://www.nsfnet-legacy.org/archives/02--Beginnings.pdf] Particularly page 38-48. 'The NSFnet Phase-I Backbone and The Fuzzball Router'- David L. Mills. 29 November 2007.</ref> allowing the testing of many of the [[Internet]]'s first protocols.<ref>[http://www.eecis.udel.edu/~mills/gallery/gallery10.html Fuzzball]: A page by [[David L. Mills]], including links to some of his papers on the Fuzzball.</ref> It allowed the development of the first TCP/IP routing protocols,<ref>{{cite book|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=Pm4RgYV2w4YC&pg=PA679|title=The TCP/IP guide: a comprehensive, illustrated Internet protocols reference|author=Charles M. Kozierok|isbn=1-59327-047-X|year=2005|publisher=No Starch Press|pages=679–681}}</ref> and the [[Network Time Protocol]].<ref>{{cite|url=http://www.crcnetbase.com/doi/abs/10.1201/b10282-20|title=Technical History of NTP}}</ref> They were the first routers to implement key refinements to TCP/IP like variable-length [[subnet mask]]s.<ref>{{cite book|title=OSPF: anatomy of an Internet routing protocol|author=John T. Moy|page=20|isbn=978-0-201-63472-3|publisher=Addison-Wesley Professional|year=1998|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=YXUWsqVhx60C&pg=PA20}}</ref>
